<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Remarks</h4>
	<div class="text"> <i>Pinus balfouriana </i>grows on several of the highest peaks in the Klamath Mountains and at timberline in the southern Sierra Nevada. Trees grow to 22 m in height, and live for up to 1000 years in the Klamath Mountains, but up to 3400 years in the Sierra Nevada. Trees produce cones after 20-50 years in age, large cone crops occur in 5- to 6-year cycles. Wind and seed-caching Clark’s nutcrackers disperse the seeds. Trees are shade intolerant. Almost all trees at timberline are erect individuals, and many may show signs of ice blasting (Sawyer 2007). <br/>
<br/>
<i>Pinus balfouriana </i>involves two subspecies (Mastroguiseppe and Mastroguiseppe 1980): ssp. <i>bal-fouriana </i>in the Klamath and Yolla Bolly mountains, and ssp. <i>austrina </i>in the southern Sierra Nevada. The ecology of the two subspecies is similar, but they can occur on different substrates (Eckert 2006, Eckert and Eckert 2007, Eckert and Sawyer 2002, Fites-Kaufman Transient; soil 2007). Stands in the Yolla Bolly Mountains exist on Franciscan greywacke sandstone, metavolcanic, and Animal; gravity; wind schist-derived substrates. Stands in the Klamath Mountains occur mostly on mafic and ultramafic substrates, with pockets of granitic and metasedimentary canopy architecture resistant substrates. Stands in the southern Sierra Nevada occur No on granitic substrates. <i>P. balfouriana </i>forms extensive stands in both regions, in which densities appear highest on steep, high-elevation slopes with southern and western aspects. Conifer richness in stands varies, with the highest conifer diversity exhibited on heterogonous surfaces in the Klamath Mountains (Eckert and Eckert 2007, Sawyer 2006, 2007). </div>
</div>

    
	
	
