    <div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
        <h4 class="header">Regional Status</h4>
        

        <ul class="text">
        
            <li><b>Klamath Mountains</b> (M261Ag, Aj, Ap, At). Stands are local at the highest elevations of Marble, Salmon, Scott, and Trinity mountains, and in the Trinity Alps. The large stand on the south slope of Mount Eddy (2735 m), included in the Mount Eddy RNA (Whipple and Cope 1979, see Cheng 2004), is exceptional in size and purity. Stands on granitic substrates in the Sugar Creek cRNA (Keeler-Wolf 1984d, see Cheng 2004) in the Salmon Mountains are species rich. Stands at Crater Creek cRNA and regionally can have up to six other conifers (Keeler-Wolf 1987b, see Cheng 2004, Eckert 2006, Eckert and Sawyer 2002): <i>Abies concolor, A.</i> x <i>shastensis, Calocedrus decurrens, Pinus jeffreyi, Pseudotsuga menziesii,</i> and <i>Tsuga mertensiana.</i></li>
        
            <li><b>Northern California Coast Ranges</b> (M261Ba). A stand sits atop South Yolla Bolly, the highest peak in the section (Eckert and Sawyer 2002, Keeler-Wolf and Keeler-Wolf 1974). Small stands also occur on North Yolla Bolly Mountain adjacent to Klamath Mountains.</li>
        
            <li><b>Sierra Nevada</b> (M261Eo, Eq-r, Eu). Stands are extensive in the Kern River and adjacent drainages in Sequoia and Kings Canyon national parks. These magnificent stands have been recently mapped and demonstrate consistent variation in associated tree species, although the stands have not been formally classified (S. Haultain, pers. com. 2006). Stands in Last Chance RNA (Keeler-Wolf 1990d, see Cheng 2004) and regionally (Eckert and Sawyer 2002, Ryerson 1983) can contain <i>A. magnifica, Juniperus grandis, Pinus albicaulis, P. flexilis,</i> and <i>P. monticola</i> trees.</li>
        
        </ul>
    </div>


    
	
<div class="allianceSection collapsable collapsed">
	 <h4 class="header">Management Considerations</h4>
	<div class="text"> Most stands are found in national parks and wilderness areas. White pine blister rust (<i>Cronartium ribicola</i>) occurs in some stands in California. Climatic change may be affecting northern populations, where they are small, isolated, and at the highest elevations (Eckert and Sawyer 2002, Howard 2004a). Populations currently are expanding down in elevation in the Klamath Mountains (Eckert and Eckert 2007). </div>
</div>

    

    

